 :tx/rationale "DEEPEST INSIGHT: The stale cache is a concurrency bug. The daemon migration is the ARCHITECTURAL fix (single writer). But there's a simpler CORRECTNESS fix: flush() should CHECK whether the disk has hashes it doesn't know about before writing. Under an exclusive file lock: current_disk_hashes = list_tx_hashes(); unknown = disk_hashes - self.known_hashes; if unknown > 0 { skip write — our cache would be a subset, next reader should rebuild }. This is ~20 LOC that prevents stale writes regardless of how many LiveStores overlap. Combined with DW0 (fingerprint from known_hashes), the result is: either we have all data and write correct cache, OR we skip and next reader gets fingerprint mismatch → rebuild. The daemon migration is STILL the right architecture (O(1) vs O(N) per command, incremental computation, event-driven guidance). But the correctness guarantee should not DEPEND on the daemon — it should hold in direct mode too. This is defense in depth at its purest: the correctness invariant holds in ALL configurations, and the daemon is a PERFORMANCE optimization layered on top."
